1.) Resource allocation and deadlock detection both seem to work properly. However, there are times when the program gets stuck and will not finish.
Other times, it will finish to completion. Sometimes, when a process becomes terminated by deadlock recovery, the program will go into an endless loop.

2.) Deadlock recovery is performed by gathering the first blocked process that contributes to the deadlock and terminating it with kill().

3.) To run the project, type "./oss" followed by any combination of these arguments (all of which are optional):
    a.) -h
    b.) -n [integer between 1 and 10]
    c.) -n [integer between 1 and 10, but less than or equal to integer for -n]
    d.) -i [integer between 1 and 1000]
    e.) -f [string for a logfile basename]

    Example: ./oss -n 6 -s 4 -i 500 -f file.txt

4.) git information can be found in the '.git' folder inside this project submission. 
